1. Lollipop Chart

  • The lollipop chart (dot plot) is visually uncluttered and easy to read, so it is used as an alternative to bar graphs and histograms.
  • Use data processed from the results of the House of Representatives elections (single-member districts) conducted from 2009 to 2014.
  • The dataset contains the following 7 variables:
Variable Name Details
year The year the House of Representatives election was held
pref Prefecture name (in Japanese)
id Prefecture id (1-47)
nosmd Total number of single-member districts in the prefecture (1-25)
ldp Total number of Liberal Democratic Party candidates elected in the prefectures single-member districts
ldp_ratio Percentage of LDP winners in the total number of single-member districts in the prefecture (%)
dpj Total number of Democratic Party candidates elected in the prefectures single-member districts
  • Download the data hr09-14_ldp_seatshare.csv
    Place it in the data folder created inside the R project folder.
  • Load this csv file and name it df_seat
df_seat <- read_csv("data/hr09_14_ldp_seatshare.csv")
  • Use the datatable() function to check the contents of the dataframe, df_seat
DT::datatable(df_seat)

1.1 1.1 Basic Lollipop Chart

  • Extract only the data from the 2009 House of Representatives election.
  • The most basic lollipop chart can be displayed as follows:
df_seat %>% 
  dplyr::filter(year == 2009) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = ldp_ratio, 
             y = pref)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  theme_bw(base_family = "HiraKakuProN-W3")+
    labs(x = "LDP Seat Share (%)", 
         y = "Prefecture")

  • Use the reorder() function to sort the prefectures in descending order of the proportion of LDP winners (ldp_ratio) to create a more readable lollipop chart.
df_seat %>% 
  dplyr::filter(year == 2009) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = ldp_ratio, 
             y = reorder(pref, ldp_ratio))) + # reorder pref based on ldp_ratio
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major.y = element_line(colour = "grey60", linetype = "dashed")) + 
  theme_bw(base_family = "HiraKakuProN-W3") +
    labs(x = "LDP Seat Share (%)", 
         y = "Prefecture")

1.2 Grouped Lollipop Chart

  • Next, using the facet() function, well display how the LDPs seat share has changed in each prefecture across the three House of Representatives elections in 2009, 2012, and 2014, using lollipop charts.
  • To display by election year (year), well convert the year variable into a factor, then sort the LDPs seat share from the 2009 House of Representatives election, and display the LDPs winning seat share for each prefecture for all three elections.
  • Well check the data type of the election year (year) used for grouping.
str(df_seat$year)
 num [1:141] 2012 2014 2009 2012 2014 ...
  • Since the variable year is numeric, convert it to factor.
df_seat$year <- factor(df_seat$year) 
df_seat %>% 
  arrange(year, ldp_ratio) %>%
  mutate(order_seq = c(1:47, rep(0, 47*2))) %>%  # add a variable `order_seq`
  
  ggplot(aes(x = ldp_ratio, 
             y = reorder(pref, order_seq))) + 
  geom_segment(aes(yend = pref),
               xend = 0, colour = "grey50") +
  geom_point(size = 2,
             aes(colour = year)) +
  scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Set1", 
                      limits = c("2009", "2012", "2014"),
                      guide = FALSE) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.y =
          element_blank()) +
  facet_grid(~ year,
             scales="free_y", space = "free_y") + 
  theme_bw(base_family = "HiraKakuProN-W3")+
    labs(x = "LDP Seat Share (%)", 
         y = "Prefecture")

The proportion of Liberal Democratic Party candidates elected in the single-member districts of the House of Representatives elections from 2009 to 2014, by prefecture.
  • If represented as a histogram, it would look like this:
# year factor 
df_seat$year <- factor(df_seat$year) 
df_seat %>% 
  arrange(year, ldp_ratio) %>%
  mutate(order_seq = c(1:47, rep(0, 47*2))) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(pref, order_seq), 
           y = ldp_ratio,  
           fill = year)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  facet_grid(~ year, scales = "free_x") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  coord_flip()+ 
  theme_bw(base_family = "HiraKakuProN-W3")+
    labs(x = "Prefecture", 
         y = "LDP Seat Share (%)")

The proportion of Liberal Democratic Party candidates elected in the single-member districts of the House of Representatives elections from 2009 to 2014, by prefecture.

Summary In the 2009 House of Representatives election, when the government transitioned from the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) to the Democratic Party, LDP members won in all the single-member districts in four prefectures: (Tottori), (Shimane), (Kochi), and (Fukui).
On the other hand, in five prefectures: (Shizuoka), (Oita), (Niigata), (Nagasaki), and (Akita), during the 2009 government transition election, LDP members were completely defeated in all the single-member districts. However, in the 2012 election, which marked the transition to the Abe administration, LDP candidates won 100% of the seats in these prefectures.
